&gt;  &gt; Anyway some may wonder why I favor QS when I do believe a reformed
&gt;  &gt; Latin alphabet is possible. There are two answers.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; The first is that like Shaw I don&#39;t think a reformed Latin alphabet is
&gt;  &gt; *politically* possible, because people will for various reasons
&gt;  &gt; disparage an orthography with diacritics, new letters, new digraphs or
&gt;  &gt; even just new spellings using the old letters and digraphs.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; The second reason is that QS is also a script reform. The Latin
&gt;  &gt; alphabet, with whatever orthography, is slow going and wasteful of
&gt;  &gt; both time and muscular effort and usually paper and ink too. For real
&gt;  &gt; speed and saving of muscular effort not even QS can beat real
&gt;  &gt; shorthand, where signs are reduced to really minimal graphic shapes.
&gt;  &gt; However shorthand has some disadvantages which QS overcomes:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;
&gt;  Yes, I agree with you. But the problem I have with QS is that although
&gt;  it saves effort to write, it requires to much effort to read back. And
&gt;  because no one else uses it, you have a code that only you can read.
&gt;
